events.description: Odo, count of Paris, is crowned king of West Francia (France) by Archbishop Walter of Sens at Compiègne.
events.html: • 888 – Odo, count of Paris, is crowned king of West Francia (France) by Archbishop Walter of Sens at Compiègne.[4]

events.description: Christopher Columbus uses his knowledge of a lunar eclipse that night to convince Jamaican natives to provide him with supplies.
events.html: • 1504 – Christopher Columbus uses his knowledge of a lunar eclipse that night to convince Jamaican natives to provide him with supplies.[5]

events.description: Abel Tasman's second Pacific voyage begins as he leaves Batavia in command of three ships.
events.html: • 1644 – Abel Tasman's second Pacific voyage begins as he leaves Batavia in command of three ships.[6][7]

events.description: In Queen Anne's War, French forces and Native Americans stage a raid on Deerfield, Massachusetts Bay Colony, killing 56 villagers and taking more than 100 captive.
events.html: • 1704 – In Queen Anne's War, French forces and Native Americans stage a raid on Deerfield, Massachusetts Bay Colony, killing 56 villagers and taking more than 100 captive.[8]

events.description: February 29 is followed by February 30 in Sweden, in a move to abolish the Swedish calendar for a return to the Julian calendar.
events.html: • 1712 – February 29 is followed by February 30 in Sweden, in a move to abolish the Swedish calendar for a return to the Julian calendar.[9]

events.description: Ulrika Eleonora, Queen of Sweden abdicates in favour of her husband, who becomes King Frederick I on March 24.
events.html: • 1720 – Ulrika Eleonora, Queen of Sweden abdicates in favour of her husband, who becomes King Frederick I on March 24.[10]

events.description: Polish nobles form the Bar Confederation.
events.html: • 1768 – Polish nobles form the Bar Confederation.[11]

events.description: The Jay Treaty between the United States and Great Britain comes into force, facilitating ten years of peaceful trade between the two nations.
events.html: • 1796 – The Jay Treaty between the United States and Great Britain comes into force, facilitating ten years of peaceful trade between the two nations.[12]

events.description: St. Petersburg, Florida is incorporated.
events.html: • 1892 – St. Petersburg, Florida is incorporated.[13]

events.description: James Madison University is founded at Harrisonburg, Virginia, United States as The State Normal and Industrial School for Women by the Virginia General Assembly.
events.html: • 1908 – James Madison University is founded at Harrisonburg, Virginia, United States as The State Normal and Industrial School for Women by the Virginia General Assembly.[14]

events.description: The Piedra Movediza (Moving Stone) of Tandil falls and breaks.
events.html: • 1912 – The Piedra Movediza (Moving Stone) of Tandil falls and breaks.[15]

events.description: Tokelau is annexed by the United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1916 – Tokelau is annexed by the United Kingdom.[16]

events.description: In South Carolina, the minimum working age for factory, mill and mine workers is raised from 12 to 14 years old.
events.html: • 1916 – In South Carolina, the minimum working age for factory, mill and mine workers is raised from 12 to 14 years old.[17]

events.description: The Czechoslovak National Assembly adopts the Constitution.
events.html: • 1920 – The Czechoslovak National Assembly adopts the Constitution.[18]

events.description: The February 26 Incident in Tokyo ends.
events.html: • 1936 – The February 26 Incident in Tokyo ends.[19]

events.description: For her performance as Mammy in Gone with the Wind, Hattie McDaniel becomes the first African American to win an Academy Award.
events.html: • 1940 – For her performance as Mammy in Gone with the Wind, Hattie McDaniel becomes the first African American to win an Academy Award.[20]

events.description: Finland initiates Winter War peace negotiations.
events.html: • 1940 – Finland initiates Winter War peace negotiations.[21]

events.description: In a ceremony held in Berkeley, California, physicist Ernest Lawrence receives the 1939 Nobel Prize in Physics from Sweden's consul general in San Francisco.
events.html: • 1940 – In a ceremony held in Berkeley, California, physicist Ernest Lawrence receives the 1939 Nobel Prize in Physics from Sweden's consul general in San Francisco.[22]

events.description: The Admiralty Islands are invaded in Operation Brewer, led by American general Douglas MacArthur, in World War II.
events.html: • 1944 – The Admiralty Islands are invaded in Operation Brewer, led by American general Douglas MacArthur, in World War II.[23]

events.description: The 5.7 Mw  Agadir earthquake shakes coastal Morocco with a maximum perceived intensity of X (Extreme), destroying Agadir and leaving 12,000 dead and another 12,000 injured.
events.html: • 1960 – The 5.7 Mw  Agadir earthquake shakes coastal Morocco with a maximum perceived intensity of X (Extreme), destroying Agadir and leaving 12,000 dead and another 12,000 injured.[24]

events.description: British Eagle International Airlines Flight 802/6 crashes into the Glungezer mountain in the Tux Alps of Austria, killing all 75 people aboard.
events.html: • 1964 – British Eagle International Airlines Flight 802/6 crashes into the Glungezer mountain in the Tux Alps of Austria, killing all 75 people aboard.[25]

events.description: Aeroflot Flight 15 crashes Irkutsk Oblast, Soviet Union, due to a loss of control. Eighty-three of the 84 occupants onboard die. The exact cause of the accident is unknown.
events.html: • 1968 – Aeroflot Flight 15 crashes Irkutsk Oblast, Soviet Union, due to a loss of control. Eighty-three of the 84 occupants onboard die. The exact cause of the accident is unknown.[26][27]

events.description: South Korea withdraws 11,000 of its 48,000 troops from South Vietnam as part of Nixon's Vietnamization policy in the Vietnam War.
events.html: • 1972 – South Korea withdraws 11,000 of its 48,000 troops from South Vietnam as part of Nixon's Vietnamization policy in the Vietnam War.[28]

events.description: Gordie Howe of the Hartford Whalers makes NHL history as he scores his 800th goal.
events.html: • 1980 – Gordie Howe of the Hartford Whalers makes NHL history as he scores his 800th goal.[29]

events.description: Pierre Trudeau announces his retirement as Liberal Party leader and Prime Minister of Canada.
events.html: • 1984 – Pierre Trudeau announces his retirement as Liberal Party leader and Prime Minister of Canada.[30]

events.description: South African archbishop Desmond Tutu is arrested along with 100 other clergymen during a five-day anti-apartheid demonstration in Cape Town.
events.html: • 1988 – South African archbishop Desmond Tutu is arrested along with 100 other clergymen during a five-day anti-apartheid demonstration in Cape Town.[31]

events.description: Svend Robinson becomes the first member of the House of Commons of Canada to come out as gay.
events.html: • 1988 – Svend Robinson becomes the first member of the House of Commons of Canada to come out as gay.[32]

events.description: A referendum is begun in Bosnia and Herzegovina for the determination of Bosnian independence.
events.html: • 1992 – A referendum is begun in Bosnia and Herzegovina for the determination of Bosnian independence.[33]

events.description: The Siege of Sarajevo officially ends.

events.html: • 2000 – Chechens attack a guard post near Ulus Kert, eventually killing 84 Russian paratroopers during the Second Chechen War.[36]

events.description: Jean-Bertrand Aristide is removed as president of Haiti following a coup.

events.html: • 2024 – The Flour massacre (also known as the Al-Rashid massacre) took place on al-Rashid street at the Al-Nabulsi roundabout to the west of Gaza City in the Palestinian territory of the Gaza Strip where more than 100 Palestinians were killed and over 750 were wounded after Israeli forces opened fire on Palestinians waiting for humanitarian aid amidst the Israel–Hamas war.[46][47]
